This is the talk page for discussing improvements to the `{{[Enwikistats](/wiki/Template:Enwikistats)}}` template. This is not a forum for general discussion about Wikipedia's statistics. Please limit discussions to proposed changes and issues with the template. New to talk pages? Welcome to the digital equivalent of a committee meeting that never ends. Please sign your posts by typing four tildes (`~~~~`).

## On the Futility of Counting

Before you descend into the usual mire of feature requests and bug reports, let's establish a baseline. This page exists to discuss `{{[Enwikistats](/wiki/Template:Enwikistats)}}`, a small box of numbers that attempts to quantify the Sisyphean task of building this encyclopedia. It's a tool for those who find comfort in metrics, a sort of digital rosary for the data-obsessed.

Discussions here should pertain directly to the template's functionality, its presentation, or its tragic inability to capture the existential weight of 6 million articles on everything from `[particle physics](/wiki/Particle_physics)` to a list of fictional badgers. If your concern is broader, might I suggest screaming into the void? Or, failing that, the `[Village pump](/wiki/Wikipedia:Village_pump)`. Adhere to the `[Wikipedia:Talk page guidelines](/wiki/Wikipedia:Talk_page_guidelines)`, not because they are particularly inspired, but because a semblance of order is all that separates us from chaos.

## The Perennial Debate Over "Active Editor"

It seems we're back here again, circling the same semantic drain. A user has, with the breathless urgency of someone who has just discovered fire, pointed out that our definition of an "active editor" (currently defined as a registered `[Wikipedian](/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedian)` with five or more edits in the last 30 days) is, and I quote, "fundamentally arbitrary."

Of course it's arbitrary. Every metric here is a ghost. We're trying to measure engagement in a project fueled by obsession, boredom, and the occasional flash of genuine intellectual curiosity. Is an `[editor](/wiki/Editor)` who makes one thousand minor `[copy edits](/wiki/Copy_editing)` more "active" than one who writes a single, comprehensive `[featured article](/wiki/Wikipedia:Featured_articles)` over six months? The template can't tell you. It can only count.

Proposing a change from five edits to six, or to a different metric entirely like "non-bot edits to mainspace," is fine. Just be aware that you are essentially rearranging deck chairs on a ship that is also the ocean. The numbers are a comforting illusion, not a reflection of value. Proceed with that knowledge, or don't. The outcome is largely the same.

## A Request for More Colors

Someone has suggested adding color-coding to the statistics. Green for growth, red for decline. An adorable suggestion, really. It presupposes a world of simple binaries, where more is always "good" and less is always "bad." Should an increase in the article deletion rate be red or green? What about a sudden spike in new user accounts, 90% of which are likely `[sockpuppets](/wiki/Wikipedia:Sockpuppetry)`?

While the aesthetic impulse is noted, turning this template into a traffic light of dubious meaning seems like a step backward. `[Data visualization](/wiki/Data_visualization)` is meant to clarify, not to create a false sense of emotional urgency. The stark, unfeeling numbers are the most honest thing about this project. Let's not dress them up in cheap sentiment. If you require a more visually stimulating experience, there are countless `[video games](/wiki/Video_game)` that can provide that for you. This is an encyclopedia. Its primary color is beige for a reason.

## The Inevitable Caching Issue

Yes, the numbers are sometimes out of date. The template, like everything else on this platform, is subject to the whims of server `[caching](/wiki/Web_cache)`. The data is pulled from a `[database](/wiki/Database)` that updates on its own schedule. The page you're viewing is a stored version of a page that was rendered at some point in the recent past. It's a snapshot of a memory of a fact.

Before you file another bug report claiming the stats are "frozen," try purging the page cache. If that doesn't work, try waiting. If that doesn't work, consider that the universe is indifferent to your need for up-to-the-second information about the number of `[disambiguation pages](/wiki/Wikipedia:Disambiguation)` on the English Wikipedia. The numbers will update when they update. This is not a high-frequency trading platform. There is no prize for knowing the article count a microsecond before anyone else. Your patience, or lack thereof, is your own problem to manage. The relevant `[parser functions](/wiki/Help:Magic_words#Parser_functions)` are doing the best they can, which is a statement that applies to most of us here.